<ActBreak
  roman="Act V"
  title="What Failed, On the Record"
  tease="Every negative result here was registered before it ran. None of them was quietly dropped."
  id="act-5"
/>

<section class="section-divider" id="negatives">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">13</span> Registered negative · throughput</div>
    <h2>If you just want volume, don't gate</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      Line the gated arm up against every baseline — prefill, logit bias, continuous flooding —
      and the humbling truth appears: <strong>continuous flooding wins raw throughput, by 6×</strong>
      (surface rate 0.96 vs 0.16), at similarly negligible entropy cost. The gated arm's registered
      throughput criterion failed at all three seeds, and the gate says <em>fail</em>.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_l21"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 13"
      alt="Two panels comparing concept surface rate and entropy cost across five steering arms"
      caption="Comparative arms, three-seed means. Left: concept surface rate — continuous flooding dominates raw surfacing. Right: entropy cost. The gated arm's value is verified placement, not volume."
      gates={["gate_L21_baselines_seed42/123/777"]}
    />

    <div class="callout green">
      <div class="callout-title">What gating actually buys</div>
      <p>
        Not throughput — <strong>legibility</strong>. Timed, verified, budgeted writes whose
        placement you can audit (2.32× more efficient per write, Act IV). If you want a firehose,
        flood. If you want a defense or an audit trail, gate. The paper says this out loud rather
        than hiding the trade.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="num-label mt-16"><span class="num">14</span> Registered negative · alignment for free</div>
    <h2>Naive steering doesn't buy alignment</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      Extract a "refusal direction" by contrastive means and steer with it — the field's standard
      move — and on an already-aligned 4B model the attack success rate goes from
      <strong>0.25 to… 0.25</strong>. Exactly nothing. A truthfulness direction: identical scores,
      both arms. Both registered, both failed, both reported. This negative is what pushed the
      project toward the recognition <em>gate</em> — the same signal, used to decide
      <em>when to defend</em> rather than as a blunt push.
    </p>

    <div class="num-label mt-16"><span class="num">15</span> Weak signal · readback</div>
    <h2>The verifier is the weakest clause</h2>

    <p>
      The doctrine says injected content should be verified by reading it back. Measured: balanced
      accuracy <strong>0.684</strong> on the dev corpus, <strong>0.637</strong> held-out (margin
      inside the binomial CI — downgraded from <em>confirm</em> to <em>screen</em> by adversarial
      review #12), and <strong>0.590</strong> pooled across three corpus styles, below the 0.6
      threshold. Corpus-amplitude coupling was confirmed in direction but failed its strict margin
      (d ≈ 0.3 vs 0.5). Readback works as a screen, not as proof — and every claim on this page
      that depends on it is labeled accordingly.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
